               <supplied reason="lost" cert="low">serv</supplied>
               <unclear>a</unclear>e <persName>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Rufus">Rufi</name>
               </persName>.</ab>
            <!-- The marked up transcription goes here, surrounded by <ab> </ab> elements -->
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>[--- sla]ve? of Rufus.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Lines 1-2: All of the deceased’s name except for “dan” is missing. If the
               genitive “Rufi” is interpreted as indicating a master-slave relationship, then the
               name is likely a single slave name. It is on this basis that Tuck tentatively
               restores “serv?]ae.” If the deceased’s name was in fact composed of a gentilicium and
               a cognomen, then “ae” in line 2 may be the ending of her cognomen.</p>
         </div>
